choices.text: not, would I have been tortured. I tried not to get into situations where I would. I tried to behave myself as much as possible, but I guess, I would have been a victim of deportation and torture and all of this if they would have found me. But my biggest worry was, of course, my mother and my neighbors. And I tried not to, my mother always told me, "Listen, you have done nothing wrong. "They will not do anything to you. "You have to be patient. "This cannot go on forever." Of course, we thought they would not go on forever, but we tried to tell ourselves this at the time. And my mother, once I throw me out of the house and I had to go to climb up into a tree. And we were near Vienna. It was somewhere near the Vienna airport. And she threw me, she threw me to the tree like this. And she said, "Look, you can climb the tree just like you climbed the ghetto walls. You can do it. Just wait." And we did. We were very patient. And I realized when I found refuge in Belgium and France and Iceland and Israel, and I married the first Israeli I met, which was not such a big accomplishment, but I finally got myself married in Israel with my wife's parents' blessings, and then we had four children, and everything looked perfect and nice and everything.
